Chris Walker seems angry. He should be grinning ear to ear as the founder of Boston-based Refine Labs, since it’s one of the fastest growing demand generation agencies of the last few years. It’s the first time we’ve met, but maybe he’s mad that he has to explain, yet again, to some old school founder (me) how marketing has changed, why the old ways don’t work.

“Most companies in this space do lead gen, not demand gen. The marketing is built around transactional conversions of contact information so you can do outbound sales. And they’ve been running the model since the early 2000s. Back then it was hard to get contact information. So the marketers created gated content. Back then it actually worked...but these leads close at a very low rate, which causes the need for a large sales organization, which is all terribly unproductive.” 

Or maybe it’s not anger I’m hearing, maybe Walker is just bitter. 

“I was working in VC funded B2B tech companies and developed a unique and effective marketing model, and I was able to get a little bit of stuff done but eventually you hit a place where you can’t keep innovating. And when I left my previous job I interviewed for Director and VP level roles and pitched companies my way of marketing and nobody wanted it.”